VALUES (
  'The Risks of Buying Presale: Developer Bankruptcies and Cancellations',
  'presale-risks-developer-bankruptcy-cancellations-bc',
  'What happens if a developer goes bankrupt in BC? Can they cancel your contract? Uzair breaks down the real risks of presale — deposit protection, cancellation clauses, the 7-day rescission period, and how to vet a developer before you sign.',
  E'You are ready to put down a $60,000 deposit on a presale condo in Surrey. But before you sign the contract, the fear sets in. You have seen the headlines about projects getting stalled and buyers losing their money.\n\nYou want to know: What happens if a developer goes bankrupt in BC? Can a developer cancel my presale contract before completion? Is buying a presale safe in the 2026 market?\n\nI am Uzair Muhammad, and I don''t deal in false promises. Buying a presale carries risk. If you don''t know how to evaluate a developer or protect your deposit, you are gambling, not investing. This guide breaks down the real risks of the BC presale market and exactly how to protect your capital.\n\n## The Reality of Developer Risk in BC\n\nThe presale market in BC is highly regulated, but it is not risk-free. When you buy a presale, you are essentially providing an interest-free loan to a developer to help them secure construction financing.\n\nIn a shifting market with high interest rates and rising construction costs, some developers get squeezed. If a developer miscalculates their budget, they may struggle to finish the building. While your deposit is held in trust, the time you lose waiting for a cancelled project is time your money isn''t growing.\n\n> The most common risk is not outright bankruptcy; it is project cancellation. A developer might cancel a project if they cannot secure enough presales to satisfy their lender, or if construction costs rise so high that the project is no longer profitable.\n\n## Why This Matters for Your Capital\n\nIf you are an investor, a cancelled project is a disaster for your ROI. Even if you get your deposit back, you have lost two years of market appreciation. You are handed back your original cash, but the market has moved on without you.\n\nIf you are a first-time buyer, a cancellation means you are suddenly thrust back into the housing market, likely facing higher prices and higher interest rates than when you originally signed your contract.\n\n> You need to know how to check a presale developer''s track record before you hand over a single dollar. A glossy brochure and a nice presentation centre tell you nothing about a developer''s financial stability.\n\n## How to Protect Your Deposit and Your Future\n\nHere is the exact framework for mitigating risk in the BC presale market:\n\n1. **Understand Deposit Protection:** What happens if a developer goes bankrupt in BC? By law, your deposit must be held in a lawyer''s trust account, not the developer''s operating account. If the developer goes under, your deposit is returned to you. However, you do not get back any lost time or potential market appreciation.\n\n2. **Review Cancellation Clauses:** Can a developer cancel my presale contract before completion? Yes. The disclosure statement will outline the specific conditions under which a developer can cancel the project (usually tied to financing or building permits). You must have a professional review these clauses.\n\n3. **Use the Rescission Period:** How does the 7-day rescission period work in BC? After you sign a presale contract and receive the disclosure statement, you have 7 clear days to walk away for any reason without penalty. Use this time to have a lawyer review the contract and finalize your financing strategy.\n\n4. **Vet the Developer:** How to check a presale developer''s track record? Look past the marketing. How many concrete towers have they actually completed? Have they ever cancelled a project? Do they have strong relationships with major lenders? Work with a realtor who knows the players, not just the projects.\n\n## The Bottom Line\n\nIs buying a presale safe in the 2026 market? It is safe if you buy from a tier-one developer with a proven track record and deep pockets. It is highly risky if you chase the lowest price per square foot from an unknown builder.\n\n> Your deposit is legally protected, but your time and market positioning are not. You must do your due diligence before you sign.\n\n## Work With a Presale Specialist\n\nStop gambling with your deposit. I am Uzair Muhammad, and I only put my clients into projects backed by developers with bulletproof track records. I know who finishes on time and who cuts corners. Book a free strategy call with me today at presalewithuzair.com, and let''s make sure your capital is secure.',
  '3adc5a81-78ff-4a19-976e-f6975217105e',
